Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation, I wanted to look at the PISA (Programme for International Student Assessment) 2012 test scores and examine Gender difference as well as differences amongst countries that are part of the OECD and countries that are not a part of the OECD.

In addition, I also wanted to look at the relationship between the Learning Time in Minutes for 3 subjects (Math, Reading and Science) and determine if I could establish a quick predictive model for the student's test grade. Although the findings in this section were initially promising when aggregating the data, the findings in this section were inconclusive on a country to country basis and the author suggests further investigating to reliably determine the relationships.

Data Overview¶

The data consisted of 480,000 rows and 635 columns. Each row represented a different student surveyed and each column represented an answer in the survey questionaire. The important columns were the ones designating

  1. The country
  2. The student's gender.
  3. The country's inclusion in the OECD

  4. The student's test scores in:

    • Math
    • Reading
    • Science

  5. The learning time in minutes/week for

    • Math
    • Reading
    • Science

The amount of countries, their inclusion in the OECD and the gender distribution¶

In total there were 65 different countries and 3 extra states within the United States of America that were investigated for a total of 68 regions/countries.

34 regions were part of the OECD and 34 regions were not part of the OECD

Each country had at least 1,500 respondents besides Liechtenstein which only had 293. The country with the most respondents was Mexico with 33806. The 3 countries with the most and the 3 countries with the least respondants are represented in a table below.

The male to female was ratio was 1:1 with approximately 240,000 males surveyed and 245,000 females surveyed.

Test results by country¶

I've decided to showcase the top 3 and bottom 3 countries in terms of Test performance in each subject (Math, Reading and Science).

The Genders are also showcased in each selected country.

In [14]:
subjects={'Math':{'index1':math_top_bottom_3, 'test_code':'PV1MATH'},'Reading':{'index1':reading_top_bottom_3,'test_code':'PV1READ'},'Science':{'index1':science_top_bottom_3,'test_code':'PV1SCIE'}};

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18, 4));

i=1
for subject in subjects:
    plt.subplot(1,3,i);
    sub_group=pisa_sub[pisa_sub.CNT.isin(subjects[subject]['index1'])];
    sb.barplot(data= sub_group, x=sub_group.CNT, y=sub_group[subjects[subject]['test_code']], hue='Gender', order=subjects[subject]['index1']);
    plt.xticks(rotation=45);
    plt.ylim(0,650);
    plt.title(str(subject) + ' results for top 3 and bottom 3 countries', fontsize=14);
    plt.ylabel('Score', fontsize=12);
    plt.xlabel('Countries', fontsize=12);
    i=i+1

As we can see, there is a stunning difference of about 200 points between the top 3 and bottom 3 countries in every test category. The gender difference is insignificant for the most part except in the reading category where females in each of the selected country outperform their male counterparts by about 20-50 points. The largest gap here is with Qatar where females score approximately 75 more points then their male counters in reading and around 50 in Science.

Test results by OECD vs Non-OECD countries along with Gender Segregations¶

In the Math category, for the OECD countries, we can notice a small gender difference in the mean and 3rd quartile in the favor of males. The same difference can be observed in the Science Test scores. This means that in OECD countries, males who perform really well slightly outperform the high achieving females.

In the Reading section, we can notice a significant difference in both categories, OECD vs Non-OECD country and Females vs Males. OECD countries score significantly higher then their non-OECD counterparts and Females score significantly higher then their male counterparts in both regions (OECD and non-OECD). Females in the OECD category at the 1st quartile (25%) would belong in the 50th percentile in Non-OECD countries, this is a major difference.

Establishing the relationship between Learning Time in minutes per week and Test Scores¶

When using the whole dataset, there appears to be a weak positive correlation between the Learning Time in minutes per week and test scores.

The respective scatter plots and heatmaps have been drawn out for all 3 subjects below.

The strongest correlation can be found in with the Science test scores

In [17]:
#dictionary with all the pair values
topics={'Math':{'Minutes':'MMINS','test_code':'PV1MATH'},'Reading':{'Minutes':'LMINS','test_code':'PV1READ'},'Science':{'Minutes':'SMINS','test_code':'PV1SCIE'} }


results= pd.DataFrame(columns=['Subject','pearsonR','p-value'])

#this part loops through the topics dictionary to get the pearson R coefficient and the p-value for the 3 pairs in topics.
for subject in topics:
    copy=pisa_sub.copy()
    copy=copy.dropna(subset=[topics[subject]['Minutes']])   #this line drops all the lines that do not contain any values
    pearsonr, pvalue = scipy.stats.pearsonr(copy[topics[subject]['Minutes']], copy[topics[subject]['test_code']])
    results.at[subject,'Subject']  = subject
    results.at[subject,'pearsonR'] = pearsonr.round(3)
    results.at[subject,'p-value']  = pvalue.round(3)


    
results.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)

results

1 Reading 0.029 0
2 Science 0.144 0

An interesting area of research for future studies: Learning time per minutes and Test Scores on a country by country basis¶

Most countries experienced a positive correlation between the Learning Time per minutes and the Test Scores. However, there were a significant amount of countries that experienced a strong negative correlation. These results were consistent amongst OECD and Non-OECD countries.

Since it is expected that Test results would increase as students spend more time learning, the author of this investigation suggests further investigations to reliably determine the relationships.

A few examples are shown below.
